<!-- ═══════ LEAD INTELLIGENCE ═══════ -->

<div class="asset">
  <h2>Lead Intelligence: What Happens Before the First Message</h2>

  <p>Every inbound lead gets profiled before the agent sends a single word. Not from a credit bureau. Not from a background check service. From five independent signals extracted from whatever data we already have.</p>

  <p>The lead comes in with a name, phone number, and the address of the ad they clicked. That's it. From those three inputs, the system builds a financial picture: estimated income, likely credit range, geographic context, employer (if they mention one in conversation), and background awareness. The profile doesn't gate the conversation — the agent doesn't refuse to talk to someone with bad credit. It shapes <em>how</em> the agent talks to them.</p>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">Signal 1: Phone Area Code (Are They Moving From Out of State?)</h2>

  <p>A 214 area code inquiring about Chicago apartments means a potential relocation from Dallas. A 312 means they're local. A 219 inquiring about Chicago is NOT a mismatch — that's Northwest Indiana, Gary, and it's a common South Side pattern. The system knows this.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Phone analysis — from lead_intelligence.py

def analyze_phone(phone, inquiry_state="IL"):
    ac = extract_area_code(phone)
    state = AREA_CODE_STATE.get(ac, "")
    metro = AREA_CODE_METRO.get(ac, "")
    mismatch = bool(state and inquiry_state and state != inquiry_state)
    return {"area_code": ac, "phone_state": state,
            "metro": metro, "mismatch": mismatch}

# Chicago metro: 312, 773, 872, 708, 630, 224, 847
# Dallas:        214, 972, 469
# Houston:       713, 832, 281
# LA:            213, 323, 310

# Special rule: 219 (NW Indiana/Gary) + IL inquiry = NO mismatch
# Common South Side pattern. Don't flag it as relocation.</pre>

  <p>The mismatch flag changes how the agent approaches the conversation. A local lead gets neighborhood-specific recommendations. An out-of-state lead gets a broader orientation — transit options, neighborhood comparisons, proximity to their employer if they've mentioned one.</p>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">Signal 2: Employer Extraction (What Do They Do for a Living?)</h2>

  <p>When a lead says "I work at UPS" in the conversation, five regex patterns try to extract the employer name. If regex finds it, Gemini Flash verifies whether it's a real company and estimates the income range. If regex finds nothing, Gemini reads the full chat and tries to extract it from context.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Employer extraction — regex first, Gemini fallback

_EMPLOYER_RE = [
    re.compile(r"i (?:work|am|been) (?:at|for|with)\s+(.+?)(?:\.|\n|$)", re.I),
    re.compile(r"(?:employed|working) (?:at|for|with|by)\s+(.+?)(?:\.|\n|$)", re.I),
    re.compile(r"my (?:job|employer|company) (?:is|at)\s+(.+?)(?:\.|\n|$)", re.I),
    re.compile(r"(?:i do|i drive for|i deliver for)\s+(.+?)(?:\.|\n|$)", re.I),
]

# If regex finds "UPS":
#   → Gemini Flash verifies: "Is this a real employer?"
#   → Returns: plausible=true, sector=logistics, size=large
#   → Income range: ($35,000, $65,000) — "employed_stable"
#
# If regex finds "attorney at Jones Day":
#   → Gemini: plausible=true, sector=legal, size=large
#   → Income range: ($55,000, $120,000) — "professional"
#
# If regex finds nothing:
#   → Gemini reads full chat context and attempts extraction

# Income categories (annual, Chicago market):
JOB_INCOME_ESTIMATES = {
    "section8_voucher": (15000, 30000),
    "employed_stable":  (35000, 65000),
    "professional":     (55000, 120000),
    "self_employed":    (25000, 60000),
    "disability":       (12000, 24000),
    "cash_worker":      (20000, 35000),
    "student":          (8000, 25000),
    "gig_worker":       (20000, 45000),
    "retired":          (18000, 40000),
}</pre>

  <p>The employer verification isn't a filter. It's context. If Gemini says "UPS — large logistics employer, stable employment," the agent knows this person probably has steady income and can qualify for most buildings. If Gemini can't verify the employer, that's a signal too. The agent doesn't stop. It adjusts.</p>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">Signal 3: ZIP Code Demographics (What Does the Neighborhood Tell Us?)</h2>

  <p>The inquiry ZIP — the address of the ad they clicked — tells you about their aspirations. It's NOT where they live. People browse aspirationally. Someone clicking on a $2,200 Lincoln Park listing might live in Englewood. The ZIP demographics provide a statistical baseline when there's nothing else to go on.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# South Side Chicago ZIP demographics — hardcoded from Census data

SOUTH_SIDE_ZIPS = {
    "60617": {"median_income": 32000, "poverty_pct": 28, "renter_pct": 65, "area": "South Shore"},
    "60619": {"median_income": 30000, "poverty_pct": 31, "renter_pct": 55, "area": "Chatham"},
    "60620": {"median_income": 33000, "poverty_pct": 25, "renter_pct": 48, "area": "Auburn Gresham"},
    "60621": {"median_income": 22000, "poverty_pct": 42, "renter_pct": 72, "area": "Englewood"},
    ...
}

# If a lead inquires from 60621 (Englewood) and we have no other income signal:
# median_income = $22,000 → max affordable rent ≈ $611/mo
# This is the LAST RESORT signal. Stated income or employer always wins.</pre>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">Signal 4: Financial Capacity (Can They Actually Afford This?)</h2>

  <p>The core rule: <code>max_affordable_rent = annual_income / 36</code>. That's the 33% rent-to-income ratio every property manager uses. The system builds the income estimate from five sources in priority order. Stated income in the chat wins. Then employer category. Then ZIP demographics. If we have nothing, the system falls back to the state median and notes the uncertainty.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Five-source financial synthesis

def estimate_financial_capacity(
    inquiry_rent=0,        # Source 1: what ad they clicked
    chat_history="",       # Source 2+3: stated budget & income
    renter_profile=None,   # Source 4: income category
    phone_state="",        # metadata
    inquiry_zip="",        # Source 5: ZIP demographics
):

# Priority order for income estimation:
# 1. Stated income in chat: "I make $55K" → $55,000
# 2. Employer category: "UPS" → employed_stable → midpoint $50,000
# 3. ZIP median income: 60617 → $32,000
# 4. State median: IL → $55,000
# 5. National default: $55,000

# Affordability gate:
max_affordable_rent = best_income_estimate / 36
affordable = effective_budget <= max_affordable_rent * 1.15

# 15% wiggle room. If they're at 35% rent-to-income, that's tight
# but not impossible. Above that, the agent knows to suggest
# alternatives: smaller unit, different neighborhood, cosigner.

# Section 8 is different — Housing Authority covers the gap
# between 30% of tenant income and the contract rent.
# Affordability check doesn't apply the same way.</pre>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">Signal 5: Credit Estimation (Without Pulling a Report)</h2>

  <p>I don't pull credit reports. The system estimates from whatever signals exist in the conversation. If they say "my credit is 720," that's the strongest signal. If they say "my credit is bad," that's clear too. If they're asking about cosigners, that tells you something. If they mention bankruptcy or eviction, that tells you more. And if they say nothing at all, the ZIP demographics provide a statistical baseline.</p>

  <p>The system also detects what I call "confident asserters" — people who say things like "my credit is fine, money is not an issue, don't worry about it." That pattern matters. If someone asserts strong standing AND we can verify their employer AND the income math works — that's a <strong>confidence case</strong>. The agent can offer a showing even with partial documentation.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Credit estimation — 6 signal types

Signal 1: Explicit score ("my credit is 720")
Signal 2: Self-reported quality ("bad credit" / "good credit")
Signal 3: Cosigner inquiry ("do you accept co-signers?")
Signal 4: Eviction history ("I was evicted" / "broken lease")
Signal 5: Bankruptcy ("chapter 7" / "discharged")
Signal 6: ZIP-based inference (lower-income ZIP → statistically lower credit)

# Confident asserter detection — specific language patterns:
"my credit is good" / "credit is fine" / "no problem there"
"I make good money" / "money is not an issue"
"I got steady income" / "don't worry about it"

# If confident asserter = true AND employer verified AND affordable:
# → CONFIDENCE CASE: STRONG
# → Recommend showing the unit even with partial docs
# → Create Asana task for building manager with full assessment
# → Continue coaxing docs: "while we get your tour set up,
#   can you snap a pic of your ID?"</pre>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">Background Awareness (Safety, Not Judgment)</h2>

  <p>The system detects sensitive situations. Reentry from incarceration. Domestic violence. Crisis housing needs. This isn't a filter — it's a tone adjustment. Someone fleeing a domestic violence situation doesn't need to be interrogated about their credit score. They need housing fast. The agent knows this and adjusts accordingly.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Background concern detection — from lead_intelligence.py

Reentry signal: "released", "incarceration", "parole", "probation"
  → "Be compassionate, non-judgmental. SAFER Foundation + St. Leonard's
     help with deposits. Background is case-by-case — older/non-violent
     usually OK."

DV/Safety: "domestic", "abuse", "restraining order", "flee"
  → "SAFETY: Possible DV situation. Prioritize speed + privacy.
     Do NOT ask why they're moving. Do NOT share their info."

Crisis housing: renter_type = "crisis"
  → "Be compassionate, not clinical. Skip interrogation. Focus on
     solving the housing problem fast. Mention HPRP and ERA programs
     that help with deposits."</pre>
</div>

<!-- ═══════ TONALITY: HOW INTELLIGENCE SHAPES THE CONVERSATION ═══════ -->

<div class="asset">
  <h2>Tonality: How the Intelligence Shapes the Conversation</h2>

  <p>All five signals — phone, employer, ZIP, financial capacity, credit — feed into the system prompt as context. Not as gates. Not as decision trees. The LLM reads the intelligence and decides how to talk to this person. The architecture is called the River Principle: every decision uses all signal sources. The intelligence shapes HOW the agent works the lead.</p>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">Renter Profiling (Via Gemini)</h2>

  <p>Gemini reads the conversation and extracts a profile: renter type, urgency, pain point, where they can bend, what could kill the deal, household composition, and language. The profile determines the tone of every subsequent message.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Renter types and how the agent adjusts

working_class:
  "Be warm, direct, no jargon. Frame costs as daily amounts.
   Don't interrogate — guide. They respect straight talk."

professional:
  "Be consultative, add value. They have options and are evaluating us.
   Curate, don't hard-sell. Anticipate their questions."

section8:
  "Be patient, encouraging. They've dealt with judgment before.
   Explain the process clearly. Voucher paperwork first.
   If new to Section 8: walk them through step by step."

student:
  "Be casual, quick. They want speed and price.
   Lead with rent and proximity to transit."

crisis:
  "Be compassionate, not clinical. They may be homeless, fleeing DV,
   or facing eviction. Do NOT ask why they need to move urgently.
   Focus on solving the housing problem fast.
   Mention Chicago rapid re-housing programs (HPRP, ERA)."</pre>

  <p>The tone map is a lookup, not an LLM call. Fast and deterministic. But it feeds INTO the LLM prompt as guidance. The LLM still generates every response from scratch — it just knows that this person is working class and wants direct answers, or that this person is a professional comparing three buildings and wants curated options.</p>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">Communication Style Detection</h2>

  <p>On top of the renter type, the system detects how the person actually texts. If their average message is under 10 characters — "ok," "yep," "how much" — they're terse. The agent matches that energy. If they use emojis in more than half their messages, the agent mirrors that. If they write formal sentences with periods and capitalization, the agent responds in kind.</p>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">Three Tonality Tiers (Locator Agent)</h2>

  <p>The apartment locator operates in three tiers based on the lead's financial profile. This isn't about being nicer to rich people. It's about matching the conversation to the reality of the deal.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Three tonality tiers — from the Locator CLAUDE.md

LOW-END (blockers, low credit, stretched budget):
  AUTHORITATIVE tone. Direct. Commanding. No hedging.
  These leads need guidance, not options.
  "I can get you into this building. Here's what you need to do."

MID-TIER (qualified, no major blockers):
  PROFESSIONAL tone. Efficient. Value-oriented.
  "I found three options in your range. Here's what stands out."

HIGH-END (2x+ median income, strong profile):
  CONSULTATIVE tone. Concierge. Curated.
  "Based on what you're looking for, I'd recommend looking at
   these two buildings. Here's why."</pre>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">What the Agent Actually Sees</h2>

  <p>All of this intelligence gets formatted into a block that's injected into the system prompt. The LLM reads it alongside the full conversation history and decides what to say next. Here's what that looks like for a real lead:</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# What the agent brain receives — formatted intelligence block

LEAD INTELLIGENCE:
PHONE: 214 (Dallas metro)
  WARNING: Out-of-state inquiry. Lead may be relocating from Texas.
EMPLOYER: UPS [PLAUSIBLE — major logistics employer, large, stable]
FINANCIAL: Inquiry rent $1,200/mo → needs ~$43,200/yr income
  Est. income: ~$50,000/yr (estimated from employed_stable)
  Rent-to-income: 29% (comfortable)
CREDIT: GOOD (self-reported, confident asserter)
  → CONFIDENT ASSERTER: Lead claims strong standing.
    Consider showing even with partial docs.
No background concerns detected.
LANE 02: QUALIFIED
  → Active lead. Keep engaging, collect docs.
CONFIDENCE CASE: STRONG — SHOW THEM THE UNIT</pre>

  <p>The agent doesn't follow rules about what to do with this information. It reads it, understands the context, and generates a response that accounts for all of it. That's the anti-determinism law: no decision trees, no templates, no "if credit is poor then send message X." The LLM reasons about the whole picture every time.</p>
</div>

<!-- ═══════ INVENTORY MATCHING ═══════ -->

<div class="asset">
  <h2>Inventory Matching: Distance, Budget, and Reasonableness</h2>

  <p>The matching algorithm is LLM-driven. I give Gemini the renter's profile, their requirements, and the available inventory. Gemini ranks properties using five weighted criteria. Neighborhood proximity is 40% of the score — calculated with geodesic distance in miles, not ZIP code approximations. Budget compatibility is 25%. The remaining 35% splits across unit specs, move-in timeline, and special needs like parking or pets.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Matching weights and distance calculation

1. NEIGHBORHOOD PROXIMITY (40%)
   → geopy.distance.geodesic(client_coords, property_coords).miles
   → Actual geodesic distance, not ZIP codes
2. BUDGET COMPATIBILITY (25%)
   → Rent within stated range, net effective rent if specials apply
3. UNIT SPECIFICATIONS (20%)
   → Bedrooms, bathrooms, dwelling type
4. TIMELINE ALIGNMENT (10%)
   → Move-in date vs vacancy date
5. SPECIAL REQUIREMENTS (5%)
   → Parking, pets, amenities

# Net effective rent:
# (Monthly Rent × 12 - Move-in Savings) ÷ 12
# $2,000/mo with 1 month free = $1,833 net effective
# Always show both when specials apply.</pre>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">Gap Analysis: What Happens When the Budget Doesn't Match</h2>

  <p>When the renter's budget doesn't match what's available, the agent doesn't say "sorry, nothing in your range." It runs gap analysis. Three tiers depending on how far the gap stretches. The gap determines the approach — reframe, value-sell, or honestly redirect.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Gap analysis framework

Gap ≤ $100:
  → "That's about a coffee a day difference."
  → Reframe as manageable. Push the property.

Gap $100-$300:
  → Value proposition. Show what the extra gets them.
  → "For $150 more you're in Lincoln Square with in-unit laundry."
  → Calculate net effective rent if move-in specials apply.

Gap > $300:
  → Deep stretch. Don't push. Be honest.
  → Widen geographic search. Drop bedroom count.
  → "Honest take — $2,200 in Lincoln Park for a 1BR is a stretch
     at your budget. But I can get you into Ravenswood for $1,700
     with the same commute."

# Budget floors (below these, there's nothing to show):
DFW:     Studio $950  | 1BR $1,000 | 2BR $1,300
Houston: Studio $900  | 1BR $950   | 2BR $1,200
Chicago: Studio $1,100 | 1BR $1,200 | 2BR $1,600</pre>
</div>

<!-- ═══════ THE AGENT BRAIN ═══════ -->

<div class="asset">
  <h2>The Agent Brain: How It Actually Works</h2>

  <p>Every agent — Locator, Landlord Rep, Ken — runs on the same core loop. The LLM receives the full conversation history, the lead intelligence, and the available tools. It decides whether to search inventory, update requirements, escalate to a human, or just respond. No orchestrator tells it what to do. The LLM reads the situation and acts.</p>

  <p>Guardrails run AFTER the LLM generates a response, not before. Rate limits, business hours, message safety, brand compliance — all post-generation filters. The LLM is the decision-maker. Guardrails are the seatbelts. This is the anti-determinism law: the LLM generates every response from scratch, with tools as capabilities it can invoke, not steps it's forced through.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Universal agent loop — from agent_core.py

1. LOAD CONTEXT
   chat history, lead intelligence, inventory, requirements

2. BUILD SYSTEM PROMPT
   persona + tools + 30+ examples + business rules as CONTEXT

3. LLM GENERATES
   response text + optional tool calls (LLM DECIDES)
   Multi-round: up to 3 tool calls per turn
   Tool results feed back → LLM generates again

4. GUARDRAILS CHECK (post-generation)
   Message safety, rate limits, brand compliance
   If blocked → response is suppressed, reason logged

5. SEND
   SMS via Twilio, webhook, or hold for human review

6. LOG REASONING TRACE
   Full audit trail: prompt length, tool calls, guardrail results,
   latency, blocked status, raw LLM output</pre>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">The Four Locator Tools</h2>

  <p>The LLM decides when to call these. No orchestrator tells it "now search inventory." It reads the conversation and decides. If the lead just told it their budget and neighborhood, it calls <code>search_inventory</code>. If the lead said "stop texting me," it calls <code>mark_dead</code>. The key instruction in the tool definition for <code>search_inventory</code>: "Don't gate this behind collecting ALL info. If you have the basics, search."</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Four tools the Locator LLM can invoke

update_requirements(client_id, budget, bedrooms, neighborhoods,
    move_in_date, credit_score, pets, cosigner, ...)
    → "Extract naturally from conversation, don't interrogate.
       You don't need all fields at once."

search_inventory(client_id, budget, bedrooms, neighborhoods)
    → "If you have the basics, search. Don't wait for everything."

escalate_to_human(client_id, reason)
    → "Legal questions, complaints, special accommodations,
       or lead explicitly asks for a person."

mark_dead(client_id, reason)
    → "ONLY when lead EXPLICITLY opts out: stop, not interested,
       found a place, scam-hostile. Do NOT mark dead for ghosts
       or slow responders."</pre>
</div>

<!-- ═══════ GKE DEPLOYMENT ═══════ -->

<div class="asset">
  <h2>GKE: What's Actually Running</h2>

  <p>The Landlord Rep agent runs on Google Kubernetes Engine in us-central1. One pod. Four containers inside it. A gunicorn web server on port 5012, a Celery beat scheduler for cron jobs, and two Celery workers for async tasks — 6 concurrent workers each, 1000m CPU and 2GB RAM per worker. The web server is the smallest container (250m CPU, 512MB). The workers do the heavy lifting.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# GKE pod architecture — homeeasy-ai-service-v3

Container 1: Web Server (gunicorn)
  gunicorn -w 1 -b 0.0.0.0:5012 app:app --timeout 60
  250m CPU, 512Mi RAM

Container 2: Celery Beat (scheduler)
  celery -A app.celery beat --loglevel=info
  500m CPU, 512Mi RAM

Container 3: Celery Worker
  celery -A app.celery worker -c 6
    --queues=ai_client_service_v3
    --time-limit=1700 --soft-time-limit=1600
    --max-tasks-per-child=10
  1000m CPU, 2Gi RAM

Service: LoadBalancer on port 5012

# Deploy pipeline (Cloud Build):
