<!-- ═══════ KEN: INSURANCE ═══════ -->

<div class="asset">
  <h2>Ken: How the Insurance Agent Sells</h2>

  <p>Ken is an SMS insurance sales agent. Outbound-first. I get a name, phone, city, and state from a partner building. Ken texts them, extracts their address and move-in date through conversation, calls the Assurant API for a real quote, sends a Stripe checkout link, and binds the policy. The critical rule: NEVER hardcode prices. Every price comes from Assurant's rating engine. If Ken quotes before calling the API, that price is a hallucination. If it's too low, the renter signs, discovers the real price, cancels, and files a complaint. If it's too high, they walk. Either way: legal liability.</p>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">Intent Classification</h2>

  <p>Every inbound message gets classified into one of 14 intents using regex patterns. The classification determines the immediate response path. "Stop" means opt out — no reply, hard stop, TCPA compliance. "Gave address" means trigger the Assurant API quote. "Is this a scam" means explain that we're licensed and Assurant-backed. "Foxen mention" means explain that Foxen is a waiver service, not actual insurance — and that if their building floods, a Foxen waiver pays them nothing.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Intent classification — from classifier.py

STOP           → Opt out immediately. No reply. TCPA compliance.
GAVE_ADDRESS   → Trigger Assurant API quote.
GAVE_EMAIL     → Store for policy delivery.
GAVE_DATE      → Store move-in date.
YES_INTERESTED → Ask for address.
PRICE_QUESTION → Collect address FIRST. Never quote before API call.
IS_THIS_SCAM   → "Licensed agent, Assurant-backed, Fortune 500 carrier."
WHO_IS_THIS    → "We got flagged that you're moving into a rental."
FOXEN_MENTION  → "Foxen is a waiver, not insurance. If your building
                   floods, a Foxen waiver pays you nothing."
ALREADY_HAS    → Verify they have $100K liability coverage.
WILL_DO_LATER  → Schedule 24h follow-up.
WANT_CALL      → Escalate to human.
NOT_INTERESTED → Mark opted out.
GENERAL_INQUIRY → Route to LLM.

# Address detection regex:
ADDRESS_PATTERN = re.compile(
    r'\d+\s+[a-zA-Z].*(?:st|street|ave|avenue|rd|road|dr|drive'
    r'|blvd|boulevard|ln|lane|way|ct|court)', re.IGNORECASE
)</pre>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">The Payment Flow</h2>

  <p>Assurant API for the quote. Stripe for the payment. PCI compliance is handled entirely by Stripe — card data never touches my servers. The checkout page is personalized: "Hey Sarah, you're almost covered!" with their name, building, coverage breakdown ($100K liability + $10K personal property), and the real premium from Assurant's rating engine.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Payment flow: Assurant quote → Stripe checkout → policy bind

Step 1: Assurant API (OAuth 2.0)
  authenticate() → client_credentials grant → access_token
  create_quote(address, coverage, dwelling_type) → premium
  # Premium varies by address, state, dwelling type.
  # $100K liability + $10K personal property is the standard tier.

Step 2: Stripe checkout session
  checkout_page_html(lead_id, first_name, building_name, premium)
  # Personalized landing page:
  #   "Hey {first_name}, you're almost covered!"
  #   Coverage: $100K liability + $10K personal property
  #   Price: ${monthly}/mo (${annual}/year)
  #   Trust badges: Secure Payment, Assurant Backed, Instant Coverage

Step 3: SMS delivery
  "Here's your checkout link: {url}"
  # Card data handled entirely by Stripe. PCI Level 1.
  # AI disclosure (mandatory): "I'm Ken, an AI assistant
  # for Jamboree Insurance."

Step 4: Policy bind
  issue_policy(quote_id, payment_token)
  # Assurant binds the policy. Renter gets confirmation.</pre>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">Drip Cadence: The Follow-Up Sequence</h2>

  <p>If someone doesn't respond, Ken follows up on a schedule: 4 hours, 24 hours, 48 hours, 5 days, 7 days. After 7 days with no response, the lead expires. Each follow-up isn't a generic nudge. The system tracks what the person said — their move date, their name, their concern, whether they said they were busy at work. The follow-up references their own words back to them. "You mentioned you're moving in on April 15th — just wanted to make sure you're covered before then."</p>
