<!-- ═══════ FINANCIAL ANALYSIS ═══════ -->

<div class="asset">
  <h2>Financial Analysis: Horizontal Truths Across APIs</h2>

  <p>The CSV parsers broke. Chase missed 42% of transactions. Wintrust missed 98%. Spirit Credit Union doesn't even offer CSV exports. The fix: stop parsing CSVs. Read the actual bank statement PDFs with pdfplumber. 367 PDFs across 6 accounts. The real financial picture came from the balance method — opening balance plus deposits minus withdrawals — not from trying to categorize individual transactions.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# Why CSVs failed (actual production test results):
Chase:     Missed 42% of transactions
Wells:     Missed 0% (good format)
Wintrust:  Missed 98% of transactions
Spirit CU: No CSV export available

# PDF balance method:
367 PDFs across 6 accounts, 7 years of data
Opening balance + deposits - withdrawals = closing balance
Cross-verified against statement ending balances: 100% accurate

# The real numbers:
Total deposits (7 years):    $1.66M
Total withdrawals (7 years): $1.67M
Lifetime position:           ~$404K-$436K loss
Texas AR write-off rate:     27%</pre>

  <h2 style="font-size:1.1rem; margin-top:3rem;">4-Tier Payment Verification</h2>

  <p>When a payment is disputed or missing, the system searches four independent sources. The consistent story across all four is what you trust. No single source tells the full picture.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# 4-tier payment verification

Tier 1: Spirit Portal (bank records)
  → ACH timestamps. Check numbers. Did the money move?

Tier 2: Invoice + lease cross-reference
  → Invoice amount vs lease terms vs deposit. Right amount?

Tier 3: Zoho Books (accounting)
  → Revenue recognition. Categorization. Tax reporting.

Tier 4: Contextual evidence
  → Email threads. SMS conversations. CRM notes.
  → "What did we promise vs what did we deliver?"

# When Tier 1 says $1,200 and Tier 2 says $1,200
# but Tier 3 says $1,100 and Tier 4 has an email saying
# "$100 discount for late maintenance" — now you have
# the full story. No single source tells you that.

# This pattern — cross-referencing independent APIs to find
# the consistent truth — applies everywhere:
#   Lead quality:   Twilio logs × CRM × conversation × outcome
#   Building value: Voice calls × ILS data × commission actually paid
#   Agent perf:     Messages sent × responses × conversions × revenue</pre>
