<!-- ═══════ GOVERNANCE ═══════ -->

<div class="asset">
  <h2>The Governance Layer: 8 Hooks, 1,334 Lines of Rules</h2>

  <p>Eight hooks across four event types. They run deterministically — can't be skipped, can't be overridden. Each one exists because of a specific production incident. The bottom-up analysis hook exists because I spent months making decisions based on a database field called <code>client_stage_progression.stage_name</code> that turned out to be garbage. The pre-bash safeguard exists because the AI tried to DROP TABLE on a production database. The session-end hook exists because I lost $4-5K per day for 8 days because sessions had no memory of what was deployed.</p>

  <pre style="background:#0a0a0a; border:1px solid #222; padding:1.5rem; font-size:0.8rem; line-height:1.6; color:#888; overflow-x:auto; margin:2rem 0;">
# 8 hooks, 4 event types — each one is a scar

SessionStart:
  pre-session-read-state.sh
  → "Read what's deployed. Read what broke. Then start."

PreToolUse (Bash):
  pre-bash-safeguard.sh
  → Blocks DROP TABLE, TRUNCATE, DELETE FROM on production
  → "Either BLOCKS or ALLOWS. That's it."

PreToolUse (SQL):
  pre-sql-bottomup.sh
  → Blocks aggregate queries before you've sampled raw records
  → "Classifiers lie. Summary fields are stale."

PostToolUse (Edit/Write):
  post-edit-lint.sh
  → Auto-lints Python. Blocks syntax errors. Detects secrets.

Stop:
  session-end-save.sh (126 lines)
  → Auto-saves session memory + git state. Detects deploys.

  stop-fresh-eyes-check.sh
  → Logs unreviewed changes. Forces review next session.

  ralph-wiggum/hooks/stop-hook.sh (178 lines)
  → Autonomous loop controller. If you promised to finish
    something and try to exit, it feeds the prompt back in.
  → Named after a Simpsons character because humor in
    infrastructure is how you stay sane at 2 AM.</pre>
</div>

